HTML (HyperText Markup Language) and CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) are both fundamental technologies used in web development, but they serve different purposes and have distinct roles in creating and styling web pages.

### HTML (HyperText Markup Language)
- **Purpose**: HTML is used to structure and organize the content of a web page. It defines the elements that make up the page, such as headings, paragraphs, images, links, and more.
- **Syntax**: HTML uses a set of tags to define elements. For example, `<h1>` for a heading, `<p>` for a paragraph, and `<img>` for an image.
- **Example**:
  ```html
  <!DOCTYPE html>
  <html lang="en">
  <head>
      <meta charset="UTF-8">
      <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
      <title>Example Page</title>
  </head>
  <body>
      <h1>Welcome to My Website</h1>
      <p>This is a paragraph of text.</p>
      <img src="image.jpg" alt="Example Image">
  </body>
  </html>
  ```

### CSS (Cascading Style Sheets)
- **Purpose**: CSS is used to style the layout and appearance of a web page. It controls the visual presentation of HTML elements, such as colors, fonts, spacing, and positioning.
- **Syntax**: CSS uses selectors to target HTML elements and apply styles. For example, `body { color: blue; }` changes the text color of the entire page to blue.
- **Example**:
  ```css
  body {
      font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
      background-color: #f0f0f0;
      color: #333;
  }

  h1 {
      color: #0066cc;
  }

  p {
      font-size: 16px;
      line-height: 1.5;
  }

  img {
      max-width: 100%;
      height: auto;
  }
  ```

### Key Differences
1. **Function**:
   - **HTML**: Structures the content.
   - **CSS**: Styles the content.

2. **Syntax**:
   - **HTML**: Uses tags to define elements.
   - **CSS**: Uses selectors and properties to style elements.

3. **Separation of Concerns**:
   - **HTML**: Focuses on the content and structure.
   - **CSS**: Focuses on the presentation and layout.

4. **Usage**:
   - **HTML**: Defines the elements and their hierarchy.
   - **CSS**: Defines the visual appearance and layout of those elements.

### How They Work Together
HTML and CSS work together to create a fully functional and visually appealing web page. HTML provides the structure, and CSS applies the styles to make the page look good. For example, you might have an HTML file that defines the content and a separate CSS file that styles that content.

```html
<!-- index.html -->
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Example Page</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Welcome to My Website</h1>
    <p>This is a paragraph of text.</p>
    <img src="image.jpg" alt="Example Image">
</body>
</html>
```

```css
/* styles.css */
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    background-color: #f0f0f0;
    color: #333;
}

h1 {
    color: #0066cc;
}

p {
    font-size: 16px;
    line-height: 1.5;
}

img {
    max-width: 100%;
    height: auto;
}
```

In this example, the HTML file defines the structure of the page, and the CSS file defines how the page should look. The `<link>` tag in the HTML file links to the CSS file, allowing the styles to be applied to the HTML elements.
